04434nam a22005655i 9780226197142DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20142014ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2014012589  a97802261971427 a10.7208/97802261971422doi  a(DE-B1597)550290  a(OCoLC)883632138  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aLC191.94b.A78 2014 4aLC191.94b.A78 2014 7aEDU0000002bisacsh04a331.11/4452231 aArum, Richard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAspiring Adults Adrift :bTentative Transitions of College Graduates /cJosipa Roksa, Richard Arum. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b12 halftones, 19 line drawings, 18 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. College and Emerging Adults -- t2. Social and Academic Learning in College -- t3. Making It in the Labor Market -- t4. Parents, Partners, and Optimism about the Future -- t5. A Way Forward -- tAppendix A: Data, Methods, and Statistical Analyses -- tAppendix B: Survey Instrument and Interview Protocol -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFew books have ever made their presence felt on college campuses—and newspaper opinion pages—as quickly and thoroughly as Richard Arum and Josipa Roksa’s 2011 landmark study of undergraduates’ learning, socialization, and study habits, Academically Adrift: Limited Learning on College Campuses. From the moment it was published, one thing was clear: no university could afford to ignore its well-documented and disturbing findings about the failings of undergraduate education. Now Arum and Roksa are back, and their new book follows the same cohort of undergraduates through the rest of their college careers and out into the working world. Built on interviews and detailed surveys of almost a thousand recent college graduates from a diverse range of colleges and universities, Aspiring Adults Adrift reveals a generation facing a difficult transition to adulthood. Recent graduates report trouble finding decent jobs and developing stable romantic relationships, as well as assuming civic and financial responsibility—yet at the same time, they remain surprisingly hopeful and upbeat about their prospects. Analyzing these findings in light of students’ performance on standardized tests of general collegiate skills, selectivity of institutions attended, and choice of major, Arum and Roksa not only map out the current state of a generation too often adrift, but enable us to examine the relationship between college experiences and tentative transitions to adulthood. Sure to be widely discussed, Aspiring Adults Adrift will compel us once again to re-examine the aims, approaches, and achievements of higher education.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCollege graduatesxEmploymentzUnited States. 0aCollege graduateszUnited StatesxAttitudes. 0aCollege graduateszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aEducation, HigherxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aEducation, HigherzUnited StatesxPublic opinion. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh1 aRoksa, Josipa, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226197142423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226197142.jpg  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles